the change from the de rigeur government. Formally the Barisan Nasional, which was in power since 1969, has been toppled by a non-Nasional coalition, the Pakatan Harapan, in the 2018 general elections. That victory was made possible by a lot of dissidents taking seats from the ruling party. This responsibility partially fell on newsworthy victorious parliamentarians such as Anwar Ibrahim, Hadi Awang, Zaid Ibrahim, among others. Some catalysts to this victory were the opposition stand in fighting public corruption, Malaysia’s declining economy and public dissatisfaction on lost promises that of old the ruling government.

Another significant event was the rakyat’s referendum on the question of Borneo’s status (Sarawak and Sabah). The two federated states are on the east side of the peninsula, seemingly looking on the future. The periphery is marginalized and forgotten about putting the future of the urban hubs, such as Kuching and Kota Kinabalu, to the curb.

In summary, not much has happened. The year 2018 has been spent in a manner that was not too different from the past two decades. There were controversies on fast food campaigns, new proposals on the “water gestation period,“ another by-election, and the sad news in Malaysia just passed six weeks ago was of a new parliamentarian from BN taking offense from having been decimated.
